\import{base-macros}

\taxon{Example}

\title{[Complete lattice](002c) for subsets ordered by inclusion}

\p{
  One of the most basic examples of a [complete lattice](002c) is the power set of a given set #{X}, denoted as #{\mathcal{P}(X)}, ordered by the subset relation #{\subseteq}. The power set #{\mathcal{P}(X)} consists of all possible subsets of #{X}, including the empty set #{\emptyset} and the set #{X} itself. If we consider the following three element set:
}
##{
  \{a, b, c\}
}
\p{
  We can draw the (complete) powerset lattice as follows:
}

\texfig{
  % https://q.uiver.app/#
  \begin{tikzcd}[column sep=small]
  & {\{a, b, c\}} \\
{\{a, b\}} & {\{a, c\}} & {\{b, c\}} \\
{\{a\}} & {\{b\}} & {\{c\}} \\
  & {\{\empty\}}
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=1-2, to=2-1]
  \arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=1-2, to=2-3]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=2-1, to=3-1]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=2-1, to=3-2]
  \arrow[dashed, tail reversed, from=2-2, to=3-1]
  \arrow[dashed, tail reversed, from=2-2, to=3-3]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=2-3, to=3-2]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=2-3, to=3-3]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=3-1, to=4-2]
  \arrow[from=3-2, to=4-2]
  \arrow[tail reversed, from=3-3, to=4-2]
  \end{tikzcd}
}

\subtree{
  \title{Some intuition}
  \p{
    There's a few observations we can make just by looking at the lattice:
  }
  \ul{
    \li{
      If we take any two subsets on the same level, such as #{\{\{a\}, \{b\}\}} then \em{two move up a level} we take the union of the sets, so:
      ##{
      \{a\} \cup \{b\} \to \{a, b\}
    }
      Conversly if we wish to \em{move down a level} we take the intersection of the two sets, so for the same pair
      ##{
      \{a\} \cap \{b\} \to \{\}
    }
      \li{
        Each level expresses the different powersets of #{X} with a given cardinality. So the bottom level is the powerset of cardinality 0 (i.e. the empty set), the next level up is the powerset of cardinality 1 (i.e. the singletons), then cardinality 2 and finally cardinality 3 at the top level which is just the set #{X} itself.
      }
      \li{
        Naturally as we move up the lattice the sets get larger (with respect to inclusion) and as we move down the lattice the sets get smaller.
      }
    }
  }
}

\p{
  As a reminder, a [complete lattice](002c) is a partially ordered set (here on inclusion) in which all subsets exhibit both a meet and join. Let's for example take the following subset:
}

##{
  S = \{\{a\}, \{a, b\}\}
}

\subtree{
  \title{Lower bound}
  \p{
    Here the lower bound is any element #{(\sqcup S) \in L} in the larger lattice in which the following property holds:
  }
  ##{
    \forall s \in S.\ (\sqcup S) \leq s
  }
  \p{
    In our case we know that #{\leq\ \equiv\ \subseteq}, furthermore we have that the elements of #{S} are the two sets #{\{a\}} and #{\{a, b\}}, hence we can rephrase this condition as
  }
  ##{
    (\sqcup S) \subseteq \{a\} \land (\sqcup S) \subseteq \{a, b\}
  }
  \p{
    Clearly the lower bound in this instance is then just:
  }
  ##{
    lb(\sqcup S) = \{\{\emptyset\}, \{a\}\}
  }
  \p{
    The greatest lower bound is simply the intersection of all lower bounds hence:
  }
  ##{
    \text{glb}(\sqcup S) = \bigcap\ \{\{\emptyset\}, \{a\}\} = \{a\}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{Upper bound}
  \p{
    The upper bound is just the flipped condition of the lower bound, i.e.:
  }
  ##{
    \forall s \in S.\ s \leq (\sqcap S) \equiv (\{a\} \subseteq (\sqcap S)) \land (\{a, b\} \subseteq (\sqcap S))
  }
  \p{
    The sets which satisfy this condition are:
  }
  ##{
    \text(ub)(\sqcup S) = \{\{a, b\}, \{a, b, c\}\}
  }
  \p{
    The least upper bound is the smallest of the sets which form the upper bound, i.e.:
  }
  ##{
    \text{lub}(\sqcap S) = \{a, b\}
  }
}
